{"query": "How does the effectiveness of community-based forest management vary across different countries according to the available evidence?", "summary": "The effectiveness of community-based forest management varies significantly across different countries according to the available evidence. In Ethiopia and Nepal, two studies including one replicated, before-and-after, site comparison found that forest cover increased more in community-managed forests than in forests not managed by local communities (Action 1152). However, in Colombia, one replicated, site comparison study found that deforestation rates in community-managed forests did not differ from deforestation rates in forests that were not managed by local communities, or in uninhabited national parks (Action 1152). 

Additional evidence from other countries shows mixed results for community-based conservation approaches. In Pakistan, involving local communities with park management was associated with an increasing population of Himalayan brown bears (Action 2395). In Brazil, areas where community-based management of fishing practices was implemented had a higher abundance of river turtles than areas with no community-based management (Action 3681). In the Philippines, after rural community members were paid a small incentive to protect Philippine crocodile sanctuaries combined with an education and awareness campaign, fewer crocodiles were killed than before community engagement (Action 3681). In Mozambique, during a community-based turtle monitoring project no killing of adults was recorded and fewer sea turtle eggs were lost to poaching than before projects began (Action 3681).

Regarding monetary incentives for forest management, results also vary by country. In Belize, numbers of black howler monkeys increased by 138% over 13 years after local communities received monetary benefits, alongside other interventions (Action 1509). In the Republic of Congo, most central chimpanzees reintroduced to an area where local communities received monetary benefits, alongside other interventions, survived over five years (Action 1509). However, in Rwanda, Uganda and the Democratic Republic of Congo, numbers of mountain gorillas declined by 28% over 41 years despite the implementation of development projects in nearby communities, alongside other interventions (Action 1509).", "action_ids": ["1152","2395","3681","1509"]}

